1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:24,957
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:26,120 --> 00:00:30,727
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:40,460 --> 00:00:46,670
So, last week we talked about what's known as the distant epoch.

4
00:00:46,750 --> 00:00:54,421
This is the story of Gautama Buddha and it's in the collection of the Jatikas.

5
00:00:55,667 --> 00:01:02,198
and we talked about what he was doing before he was born as a bodhisattva.

6
00:01:03,740 --> 00:01:17,641
And I was going to go on to the process of his life and what he did during his life, but then it occurred to me that this was a good time to look at the

7
00:01:18,128 --> 00:01:32,447
Parami, because herein our Bodhisattva spent four asankhaya, measureless times, and hundred thousand eons, making his resolutions under twenty-four Buddhas, commencing with Deepankara.

8
00:01:33,608 --> 00:01:39,596
No Buddha other than this perfectly enlightened one appeared after the Blessed One, Kassapa.

9
00:01:40,335 --> 00:01:48,864
And in this manner, the Buddha received his assurance under the 24 Buddhas, beginning with Dipankara.

10
00:01:48,884 --> 00:01:53,067
So, what was he doing during that hell of a long time?

11
00:01:53,487 --> 00:01:55,950
My goodness, what was he playing at?

12
00:01:56,790 --> 00:01:57,712
That took him so long.

13
00:01:58,371 --> 00:02:01,234
So it was the development of these parami.

14
00:02:01,816 --> 00:02:07,760
And they're usually described as perfections, which is a little bit over the top, really.

15
00:02:08,197 --> 00:02:17,349
It's more virtues or those qualities that you need to get to the other shore, because that's what parami means, the other shore.

16
00:02:19,513 --> 00:02:23,419
But he needs a little bit more than that, and I just want to read this just out of interest to you.

17
00:02:24,219 --> 00:02:31,711
He actually needs, for it is said, the resolution which consists of a combination of eight conditions.

18
00:02:31,991 --> 00:02:34,914
You can't just become a Buddha because you've got the perfections right.

19
00:02:36,437 --> 00:02:37,579
Birth as a human being,

20
00:02:38,301 --> 00:02:39,604
The advantage of sex.

21
00:02:39,864 --> 00:02:40,844
We'll come to that in a minute.

22
00:02:41,366 --> 00:02:42,567
No throwing stones yet, please.

23
00:02:44,049 --> 00:02:45,030
The good fortune.

24
00:02:45,070 --> 00:02:47,312
The meeting with a teacher.

25
00:02:49,616 --> 00:02:50,217
Ordination.

26
00:02:50,837 --> 00:02:54,102
Endowment of inherent capabilities to higher knowledge.

27
00:02:55,503 --> 00:02:58,247
The dedication of one's life and resolute will.

28
00:02:58,927 --> 00:03:00,150
So there's one or two things there.

29
00:03:02,372 --> 00:03:04,495
The idea that you have to be a human being to be a buddha.

30
00:03:04,829 --> 00:03:06,009
You can't do it in the other realms.

31
00:03:06,570 --> 00:03:08,252
So I think we know why.

32
00:03:08,551 --> 00:03:12,975
You know the hell realms are too painful and the heavenly realms are just too joyful.

33
00:03:13,336 --> 00:03:17,901
The wonderful thing about the human realm, it has this lovely mixture of joy and woe.

34
00:03:20,302 --> 00:03:23,026
And of course we have the intelligence to work our way out of it.

35
00:03:24,806 --> 00:03:33,435
The advantage of sex, if you remember last time we were talking about conceptions of time and the idea of circular time.

36
00:03:33,854 --> 00:03:42,784
So obviously if you believe in circular time, time constantly repeating itself, then once you've got a Buddha who is a male, all the rest of them have to be males.

37
00:03:44,487 --> 00:03:49,274
That's what you call a ditti, that's what you call holding on to a belief, you see.

38
00:03:50,294 --> 00:03:52,337
And the Buddha rails about this.

39
00:03:52,418 --> 00:03:58,224
If he knew what was being said about him now, I'm sure he'd turn over in his grave if he was still there.

40
00:03:58,829 --> 00:04:08,264
The whole idea of extending something present into the past to make a law of it is one of those things that we constantly do.

41
00:04:08,324 --> 00:04:11,650
Precedence.

42
00:04:11,669 --> 00:04:14,975
In our law-making we call it precedence.

43
00:04:14,996 --> 00:04:17,959
So that's how you end up with the idea that only men can become Buddhas.

44
00:04:20,964 --> 00:04:25,612
The meeting with a teacher or a nation, endowment of inherent capabilities to higher knowledge.

45
00:04:27,095 --> 00:04:34,305
Hopefully we've all got that, but there's something perhaps special about somebody who's made that dedication to become fully self-enlightened.

46
00:04:35,767 --> 00:04:38,732
And a dedication of one's life and resolute will.

47
00:04:39,052 --> 00:04:39,612
Don't forget that.

48
00:04:40,935 --> 00:04:49,247
This endowment of inherent capabilities to the higher knowledge.

49
00:04:49,266 --> 00:04:55,295
So remember, we've all got that, but we talk about the self-enlightened Buddha,

50
00:04:55,732 --> 00:05:00,819
So for a Westerner, this does conjure up the idea of the self-made man, the self-made woman.

51
00:05:01,920 --> 00:05:20,826
And of course, when you look into the history of anybody who is self-made in terms of their success in society, you find that they've been helped along by their workers, by the system, by their birth, by good fortune, and so on and so forth.

52
00:05:21,286 --> 00:05:25,451
So the idea of somebody being self-made is one of these lovely Western myths.

53
00:05:25,870 --> 00:05:29,173
And we deposit that on the Buddha, thinking that he did it all by himself.

54
00:05:29,874 --> 00:05:31,716
So, of course, he didn't.

55
00:05:31,737 --> 00:05:42,367
He started off by going to teachers, tried various methods, as you know, and eventually, in that despair, suddenly found a way out of the problem.

56
00:05:42,848 --> 00:05:44,571
But we'll come to that perhaps at another time.

57
00:05:46,392 --> 00:05:54,661
So what I want to just talk around, really, just allow ourselves to contemplate a little, are these...

58
00:05:55,266 --> 00:05:59,533
but I want to do it specifically for a retreat situation.

59
00:06:02,137 --> 00:06:07,326
The first two I'll sort of stick together are dana, generosity, and metta.

60
00:06:10,009 --> 00:06:12,653
So, you know, we say that charity begins at home.

61
00:06:12,995 --> 00:06:14,177
So where's home, you see?

62
00:06:14,237 --> 00:06:14,997
It's here, isn't it?

63
00:06:15,377 --> 00:06:18,302
It's how I treat myself.

64
00:06:18,322 --> 00:06:22,810
If I can discover and develop a way of treating myself, which is

65
00:06:23,194 --> 00:06:28,540
virtuous and which does me good, then let's presume that I'm going to treat others in the same way.

66
00:06:30,362 --> 00:06:34,747
So we have this, there's a teaching called the ahara or nutriments.

67
00:06:35,668 --> 00:06:37,149
And they go like this.

68
00:06:37,449 --> 00:06:39,572
Food for the body, that's pretty straightforward.

69
00:06:40,252 --> 00:06:41,814
Sense impression for feeling.

70
00:06:42,475 --> 00:06:48,661
Volition for sankara, for mental formations or becoming, karma.

71
00:06:49,641 --> 00:06:52,105
And consciousness for the body-mind.

72
00:06:52,641 --> 00:06:58,497
That one specifically has to do with the process of rebirth, so we didn't bother ourselves here so much.

73
00:06:58,978 --> 00:07:03,108
But it's this concept of nourishing, nourishing ourselves.

74
00:07:04,911 --> 00:07:09,603
So when we go for food, you see, that's a real opportunity to develop this nourishment.

75
00:07:09,802 --> 00:07:13,086
dana, this generosity, this nourishment towards ourselves.

76
00:07:13,927 --> 00:07:29,944
So you have to, as it were, get in contact with the body and you have to recognise that the feelings of hunger partly are coming from the body itself needing nourishment and partly from greed which also needs nourishment.

77
00:07:31,105 --> 00:07:39,252
So we have to be able to recognise that that's there whether we like it or not and it's a case of approaching the food with that

78
00:07:39,773 --> 00:08:06,422
consciousness of the body with that awareness of the feelings in the body and then reminding ourselves that we can always go for seconds we take what we feel we need and we place it in front of us you see and again to remind ourselves that this is nourishment for the body that it's just going to cause us the sufferings of greed if we indulge so we begin to eat

79
00:08:06,637 --> 00:08:22,194
Now, at this point, you see, especially with this teaching around dukkha and suffering and all that, and the dangers of pleasure, we often fall into the wrong thinking that pleasurable feelings are somehow evil.

80
00:08:23,396 --> 00:08:27,040
You have to be very careful with pleasant feelings.

81
00:08:27,781 --> 00:08:31,324
They're mara in disguise, and they're going to drag you down to an eternal hell.

82
00:08:32,365 --> 00:08:36,509
In which case, you fall into the error of self-mortification, because now

83
00:08:36,861 --> 00:08:38,443
you don't let yourself enjoy anything.

84
00:08:38,724 --> 00:08:41,326
Because if you enjoy something, well, surely that's the same as greed.

85
00:08:42,849 --> 00:08:52,761
So, this distinction between enjoying what is given to us and indulging it is obviously very subtle.

86
00:08:53,241 --> 00:08:56,605
And we fall into the error of one or the other.

87
00:08:58,048 --> 00:09:02,092
In the monastic life, which I've come to know a little bit about,

88
00:09:02,461 --> 00:09:11,373
The horror sometimes comes out in people's practice, the horror of any sort of sense pleasure.

89
00:09:12,634 --> 00:09:22,268
Monks will ride on buses and trains and keep their eyes constantly on their knees, daring not to look out in case they're distracted by whatever passes by.

90
00:09:23,929 --> 00:09:31,640
And there was one lovely example I remember of a monk who, if you saw him, you would definitely feel that he was an ascetic of tremendous wisdom.

91
00:09:31,908 --> 00:09:59,501
stature he had that gaunt look about him of somebody who had been through hell and survived and he was a couple of years older than me in the order so he would sit to my left you see and the food came by and it happened to be a very lovely meal it was somebody's birthday so it was one of these times when we got fruit salad with ice cream so this was there this was served to us and um

92
00:10:00,544 --> 00:10:08,432
We began eating it, the road monks, and I noticed that he was actually staring at this object on the table.

93
00:10:09,293 --> 00:10:12,496
And I could feel the energy of his stare, you see.

94
00:10:13,158 --> 00:10:16,902
Because right there in front of him was Mara, you see.

95
00:10:16,922 --> 00:10:29,134
And as we ate it and we got close to finishing our dessert, he very mindfully went towards it, picked it up very gently, raised it to his lips, and...

96
00:10:31,222 --> 00:10:39,538
disappeared within a couple of seconds, just in case it touched the tongue, just in case there arose anywhere some sort of pleasurable feeling.

97
00:10:41,722 --> 00:10:49,758
Now you can imagine that this sort of life is pretty dire if you can't enjoy what life gives us.

98
00:10:49,918 --> 00:10:53,264
We're very familiar with the genres and the idea that we can

99
00:10:53,548 --> 00:11:20,248
sail into jhanas and that the buddha said that this was wonderful but there is a point in the scriptures where the buddha coming back from alms round actually says to ananda why don't we find a beautiful shrine where we can eat this a park remember shrines in those days were really like parks and he names a couple of shrines the chapel a shrine is the one i remember and um

100
00:11:21,139 --> 00:11:25,168
The question arises, why should he be bothered about eating his food in a beautiful shrine?

101
00:11:25,408 --> 00:11:27,172
Why not on a dung heap?

102
00:11:27,932 --> 00:11:29,856
Or in a desert place, or just where he is?

103
00:11:30,839 --> 00:11:43,062
So there's something about beauty, there's something about the loveliness of life, which is not to be confused with indulgence and wrong relationship, which causes us problems.

104
00:11:44,022 --> 00:11:53,033
Now, it seems to me that food is just one of these lovely places where we can develop this right attitude because we have to eat.

105
00:11:54,095 --> 00:12:04,106
And most of us do it two, three times a day and probably a lot more often as well with the cups of teas and coffees and what have you.

106
00:12:04,778 --> 00:12:19,615
So every time we approach something to nourish the body, there's an opportunity to make this distinction between enjoying what is lovely, what is beautiful, and indulging in it.

107
00:12:20,796 --> 00:12:30,567
Now it seems to me that if we can crack this problem of enjoying something without indulgence, of experiencing essential pleasure,

108
00:12:31,052 --> 00:12:40,222
in a lovely way, without indulgence, then we have perhaps a way of translating that into every part of our lives.

109
00:12:41,764 --> 00:12:45,008
So there's of course all the joys of relationship.

110
00:12:45,028 --> 00:12:50,133
How can you enjoy the joys of relationship without becoming attached?

111
00:12:52,034 --> 00:12:53,376
There's got to be a way of doing it, surely.

112
00:12:54,597 --> 00:12:57,380
How can you enjoy all the aesthetic beauty of life

113
00:12:58,340 --> 00:13:01,182
And not depend upon it for personal happiness.

114
00:13:01,943 --> 00:13:03,505
That's what indulgence does, doesn't it?

115
00:13:03,745 --> 00:13:05,648
You depend upon.

116
00:13:05,668 --> 00:13:08,471
Your happiness depends upon something being there.

117
00:13:10,193 --> 00:13:21,365
And when it comes even to the spiritual joys, you see, one of the warnings that they always tell you about jhana practice is that you get stuck with it.

118
00:13:21,426 --> 00:13:24,330
You become indulgent and you can't let it go.

119
00:13:24,370 --> 00:13:26,371
And it just becomes another path to hell.

120
00:13:26,892 --> 00:13:46,975
So it seems to me that this dana, this generosity that we can practice towards ourselves, this loving kindness, this caring towards ourselves, if we start just with the basic, the basic body, what does the body need and how can I give it to the body in a way which is lovely, which is beautiful.

121
00:13:53,163 --> 00:13:55,667
When it comes to...

122
00:13:56,692 --> 00:14:02,480
In meditation, you know, keeping the mind calm, keeping the mind still.

123
00:14:03,383 --> 00:14:05,926
Remember that you have to nourish that.

124
00:14:06,187 --> 00:14:13,857
You have to nourish that by giving it those things to absorb into, as it were.

125
00:14:14,298 --> 00:14:15,879
So just the softness of the breath.

126
00:14:16,961 --> 00:14:21,148
So instead of looking at it as some sort of painful exercise that one has to do,

127
00:14:21,500 --> 00:14:50,663
to watch the breath in order to make insight feel the actual gentle feelings of the breath feel that lovely quality of the breath and just those calm gentle feelings around it and just begin to sense that as something which is worthy of appreciation the body does have lovely feelings now

128
00:14:51,841 --> 00:15:00,229
Going always with this idea of giving oneself something is, of course, the opposite, which is to renounce.

129
00:15:00,369 --> 00:15:01,610
You've got to renounce something.

130
00:15:02,792 --> 00:15:05,835
And that's where you get these two particular paramis.

131
00:15:05,875 --> 00:15:10,759
They come together, the idea of generosity, the idea of giving, and the idea of renunciation.

132
00:15:11,620 --> 00:15:21,730
So in ordinary daily life, when we give something to somebody with no hope of return, it means we have to give something up, which we would have normally used for our own personal enjoyment.

133
00:15:22,267 --> 00:15:36,668
If you make a donation, shall we say, to these terrible things that happen in nature, and you make a donation to help people, then you've obviously given something up, which you might have had before.

134
00:15:36,688 --> 00:15:41,096
You might have gone on holiday somewhere, but you've decided to give that up for the benefit of others.

135
00:15:41,917 --> 00:15:48,827
So the idea of renunciation and generosity and care always balance each other.

136
00:15:48,847 --> 00:15:49,489
They come together.

137
00:15:51,089 --> 00:16:03,062
So when we nourish the mind, when we want to nourish our calmness within us, remember that it also means that we have to renounce sense pleasure.

138
00:16:03,761 --> 00:16:05,804
Now it's up to you how far you want to take that.

139
00:16:08,006 --> 00:16:09,589
Reading can excite the mind.

140
00:16:10,328 --> 00:16:11,791
Writing can excite the mind.

141
00:16:12,652 --> 00:16:15,774
Phone calls and definitely getting onto the web.

142
00:16:16,475 --> 00:16:20,320
So all these things have to be renounced.

143
00:16:20,636 --> 00:16:22,938
for the benefit of spiritual development.

144
00:16:23,620 --> 00:16:33,249
You can even get more refined and, of course, not look around, not look around at nature, which is around us here, and just keep the eyes, as it were, still.

145
00:16:33,889 --> 00:16:37,052
So this feels like a sort of sensory deprivation.

146
00:16:37,393 --> 00:16:40,556
But the purpose, of course, is to completely calm the mind.

147
00:16:41,636 --> 00:16:46,020
And the more we stop that sense impression, you see, the more the mind will calm.

148
00:16:46,301 --> 00:16:47,201
It's just a fact.

149
00:16:49,325 --> 00:16:52,970
These sense impressions, remember, are what feelings are made out of.

150
00:16:53,210 --> 00:16:58,918
So as soon as a sense impression comes in, we immediately perceive it as either being pleasant or unpleasant.

151
00:16:59,740 --> 00:17:03,585
And as soon as that happens, you get your reaction, wanting, not wanting.

152
00:17:04,526 --> 00:17:17,443
So to keep the mind very calm, you see, and to restrict your sense perception at all the doors, hearing, whatever, is going to help us to just calm the mind.

153
00:17:17,503 --> 00:17:18,605
It's sort of,

154
00:17:18,855 --> 00:17:21,601
Feeding the calmness, nourishing the calmness.

155
00:17:21,861 --> 00:17:25,827
And calmness, remember, Pasadi, is one of the seven facts of enlightenment.

156
00:17:26,409 --> 00:17:27,230
So it's all linked.

157
00:17:27,892 --> 00:17:28,673
Everything's linked.

158
00:17:33,121 --> 00:17:34,644
This lovely word, attention.

159
00:17:36,527 --> 00:17:37,950
It has this double meaning, doesn't it?

160
00:17:38,009 --> 00:17:43,159
To attend to somebody, to look after them, to tend to something.

161
00:17:43,644 --> 00:18:01,258
And by paying attention to the object, by giving it a feeling of care towards what you're looking at, giving a flavor of loving kindness to your practice, looking down upon something with compassion.

162
00:18:02,038 --> 00:18:07,189
So we have this Buddha, Avalokitesvara, from the Mahayana tradition,

163
00:18:07,372 --> 00:18:09,976
to look down upon, to look down upon with compassion.

164
00:18:10,556 --> 00:18:22,211
So when these great pains arise in the body, which, remember, are only trying to express themselves, one looks down upon them with great compassion.

165
00:18:23,252 --> 00:18:35,589
As it were, one embraces them, opens up to them, but rather than always this sort of very sharp investigation, which is fine, I mean, there's nothing wrong with that,

166
00:18:36,176 --> 00:18:41,801
but sometimes just to, as it were, flavour the investigation with just that little bit of kindness.

167
00:18:42,442 --> 00:18:44,884
And what that tends to do is it just softens a bit.

168
00:18:45,226 --> 00:18:47,027
It just softens the process, that's all.

169
00:18:48,429 --> 00:18:55,915
Of course, the danger there is that you try and zap what it is that's hurting you with enormous compassion and try and do a bit of New Age healing.

170
00:18:56,736 --> 00:19:00,119
And of course, that can be a disaster, especially if it fails.

171
00:19:01,980 --> 00:19:05,744
So it's a case of also recognising that

172
00:19:06,568 --> 00:19:11,175
The attention that we pay, the attention can be an attending, an attending to.

173
00:19:11,236 --> 00:19:28,000
And if we think of the body with its pains coming either from the physical base, from the posture, say from the knees and things like that, or from the turbulences that are caught up, these mental turbulences that are caught up in the body that come out as neck ache, back ache, stomach ache, the whole load of aches.

174
00:19:28,721 --> 00:19:34,450
And to, as it were, look down upon them with that sort of gentleness, you know.

175
00:19:35,948 --> 00:19:39,413
So this is a generosity, this is a kindness, isn't it?

176
00:19:39,433 --> 00:19:45,864
This is a kindness towards ourselves.

177
00:19:45,884 --> 00:19:49,630
There's also to nourish that sense of enthusiasm.

178
00:19:49,650 --> 00:19:56,942
It doesn't come, I mean, sometimes it just arises of itself, but enthusiasm sounds vaguer, a sense of urgency.

179
00:19:56,961 --> 00:19:58,664
You have to feed it, you have to

180
00:19:59,101 --> 00:20:08,071
Sometimes when you find yourself not putting in the practice, it's sometimes because we haven't lifted that enthusiasm.

181
00:20:09,753 --> 00:20:17,443
If you think of people in the business world or the political world, how they're constantly telling themselves to get on with it.

182
00:20:17,964 --> 00:20:24,432
These sports people that shout at themselves to make the game, you say, well, I'm not suggesting that you do that.

183
00:20:24,598 --> 00:20:30,969
But one has to, as it were, bring up what were the reasons that we came to meditation for in the first place.

184
00:20:31,169 --> 00:20:34,294
You have to keep reminding yourself.

185
00:20:34,473 --> 00:20:39,863
You have to cajole yourself sometimes to build up that dedication.

186
00:20:41,566 --> 00:20:52,142
So this is all to do with not being hard upon ourselves, but just to develop this sense of generosity towards ourselves.

187
00:20:55,362 --> 00:20:57,285
It's the same with concentration, you see.

188
00:20:57,484 --> 00:21:06,257
When you don't have concentration, then you can get very down and you start blaming yourself and you think, oh dear, this is terrible and all this sort of stuff.

189
00:21:06,277 --> 00:21:12,525
And it's a case of just resting and just asking yourself, well, why isn't it coming, you see?

190
00:21:13,145 --> 00:21:17,471
So then if you put too much energy into it, of course, then it corrupts it even further.

191
00:21:17,451 --> 00:21:20,095
So it has to be a gentle energy, a cajoling.

192
00:21:20,816 --> 00:21:24,160
Have some sort of image, like training a puppy dog to sit.

193
00:21:24,559 --> 00:21:26,221
If you give it a kick, it just runs away.

194
00:21:26,623 --> 00:21:29,526
So you've got to pat it down and give it something to suck.

195
00:21:30,086 --> 00:21:33,150
And very slowly, it'll sit down for you.

196
00:21:33,570 --> 00:21:38,737
So that sense of being kind to oneself, being generous to oneself.

197
00:21:40,198 --> 00:21:46,125
In all the forms of our practice, we can find a little way of bringing that generosity towards it.

198
00:21:51,691 --> 00:21:59,799
Of course, there is always going to be the danger of indulgence, but sometimes give yourself the benefit of the doubt.

199
00:22:01,040 --> 00:22:04,744
You are actually being caring and not indulging.

200
00:22:04,884 --> 00:22:10,109
I think the trick is to really look at your attitude.

201
00:22:10,570 --> 00:22:11,811
Why am I doing it?

202
00:22:12,752 --> 00:22:14,434
And sort of be very clear about that.

203
00:22:15,875 --> 00:22:21,241
And that brings us really to this whole business of honesty.

204
00:22:22,099 --> 00:22:27,828
Honesty is, I mean, nobody would say, you know, I'm telling lies or anything.

205
00:22:27,888 --> 00:22:28,871
It's not a case of that.

206
00:22:29,271 --> 00:22:31,595
It's a case more of exaggeration or not.

207
00:22:31,935 --> 00:22:35,902
Not really facing up to why you're doing something.

208
00:22:36,222 --> 00:22:42,212
So you feel a bit sleepy and, you know, a little power nap, take a bit of time out, all this sort of stuff.

209
00:22:42,232 --> 00:22:43,595
You know, I'm being kind to myself.

210
00:22:44,296 --> 00:22:47,922
But actually, when you really quiz yourself,

211
00:22:48,239 --> 00:23:00,590
and you recognize that you've actually had a very good night's sleep, and really there's no reason at all to fall asleep at this present time, then one has to be kind to oneself by not going to sleep.

212
00:23:01,731 --> 00:23:07,057
Or else one simply begins to develop that idea of little naps all over the place.

213
00:23:07,636 --> 00:23:12,080
And if you've ever tried that, it does undermine your meditation.

214
00:23:12,101 --> 00:23:14,202
It begins to actually sap your energy.

215
00:23:14,363 --> 00:23:15,984
So you have to be slightly careful about that.

216
00:23:17,634 --> 00:23:30,476
And that truthfulness, you know, even small things like, what we want to do, don't we, is to build up this, to build up the power of our meditation.

217
00:23:30,935 --> 00:23:34,642
We want to maintain a constant effort, a constant effort.

218
00:23:35,503 --> 00:23:39,470
And I personally like to think in three hour blocks, I can sort of handle that.

219
00:23:39,490 --> 00:23:41,854
If it gets longer than that, I get headaches and stuff like that.

220
00:23:42,374 --> 00:23:43,737
So a three-hour block.

221
00:23:43,797 --> 00:23:50,974
So if I've been sitting, say, for one hour, and then I get up, you see, well, there's that little idea comes, you know, have a cup of tea.

222
00:23:51,796 --> 00:23:54,122
And off I go, and half an hour goes having this.

223
00:23:54,625 --> 00:24:24,143
cup of tea which i never needed anyway and of course it ruins it ruins that little special effort it ruins the building up of that energy that we need to uh to um to really make some good insight so um when when you when you when you get these feelings to have a little drink or take a little break or go for a little walk so you have to be really truthful you have to sit there and say now come on you know and then you and then you you go to the walking place and do your walking meditation and uh

224
00:24:24,375 --> 00:24:31,384
Very slowly, you see, by renouncing those, you see, they're all nicely interwoven, these things.

225
00:24:31,443 --> 00:24:44,758
By renouncing those desires, one is being kind to oneself and one is building up this other parami, this other virtue of determination, adhitani, you see.

226
00:24:45,598 --> 00:24:47,480
Goodwill, strong will.

227
00:24:49,469 --> 00:24:55,055
One of those things is when you feel restless and you think, oh well, I'll go for a walk.

228
00:24:55,275 --> 00:24:56,436
The mind is not still.

229
00:24:57,657 --> 00:25:00,260
And off you go, you go into the forest or something, you see.

230
00:25:01,261 --> 00:25:03,483
And really, you're just escaping.

231
00:25:04,224 --> 00:25:07,469
We're just wandering off to get away from restlessness for a little bit.

232
00:25:07,489 --> 00:25:13,115
And of course, if you do feel restless and we walk fast up and down, it does give us a sense of relief.

233
00:25:13,734 --> 00:25:18,800
But it's not dealing with the mental factor of restlessness at all.

234
00:25:19,844 --> 00:25:22,747
And often we can use that to suppress.

235
00:25:23,228 --> 00:25:24,710
So you have to be careful.

236
00:25:25,190 --> 00:25:28,233
So it's the same with sloth and torpor.

237
00:25:28,554 --> 00:25:30,676
I prefer the words dullness and lethargy, frankly.

238
00:25:32,858 --> 00:25:40,008
Dullness and lethargy, you can make the mistake of thinking, right, well I'll go for a run and really shake this off.

239
00:25:40,588 --> 00:25:47,656
And of course what you're doing is you're suppressing those feelings which are an energy force, which is drawing us down.

240
00:25:48,328 --> 00:25:55,527
There's energy, remember, which bursts us out like stars, and there's energy which draws us down like black holes.

241
00:25:56,208 --> 00:26:00,499
So it's all within us, and if we think that we're going to overcome...

242
00:26:00,849 --> 00:26:06,416
Feelings of sloth, dullness and lethargy by giving ourselves a kick and running about.

243
00:26:07,378 --> 00:26:12,444
That's just another way of actually suppressing it and building over it this energy.

244
00:26:13,967 --> 00:26:21,356
But actually we're not dealing with this energy which is experienced as a dullness in the mind or a heaviness in the body.

245
00:26:21,741 --> 00:26:32,021
so how do we do that you see well again you have to let go of the idea of trying to do something about it

246
00:26:32,221 --> 00:26:35,223
And as it were, be gentle to these things.

247
00:26:35,344 --> 00:26:36,665
Be generous to these things.

248
00:26:36,726 --> 00:26:37,846
Be open to these things.

249
00:26:37,987 --> 00:26:39,989
And allow them to express themselves.

250
00:26:40,609 --> 00:26:45,454
So you have to find a way of allowing dullness and lethargy to express itself.

251
00:26:46,375 --> 00:26:49,138
And usually the best way is to walk up and down gently, you see.

252
00:26:49,278 --> 00:26:52,162
But you keep your mind, you keep your attention on those feelings.

253
00:26:52,803 --> 00:26:59,269
And in that way, these mental states are given the space to and the time just to exhaust themselves.

254
00:27:01,051 --> 00:27:01,451
Often,

255
00:27:01,786 --> 00:27:06,810
When we do that we can feel that transformation.

256
00:27:07,070 --> 00:27:09,692
So remember that there's nothing lost in this process.

257
00:27:09,794 --> 00:27:11,434
Everything is simply transformed.

258
00:27:11,795 --> 00:27:19,221
So we might just suddenly feel having worked with these feelings of dullness and lethargy a sudden very gentle energy.

259
00:27:20,344 --> 00:27:23,967
Sometimes it flips because it's just the other side of the coin of restlessness.

260
00:27:26,409 --> 00:27:29,311
So it's a case of being careful to

261
00:27:29,730 --> 00:27:33,936
really be truthful with ourselves, not to kid ourselves.

262
00:27:34,037 --> 00:27:46,494
Of course, the opposite is, or the danger, of course, is you get into self-criticism, self-judgment, this business of I'm no good, everybody else can do it but not me, I'm special that way.

263
00:27:47,517 --> 00:27:54,626
And it's a case of recognising that you have to make a separation between the action and the person.

264
00:27:55,087 --> 00:27:57,211
The person is a figment of the imagination.

265
00:27:57,791 --> 00:27:58,573
We can say that

266
00:27:58,823 --> 00:28:00,365
This action was unskillful.

267
00:28:02,749 --> 00:28:06,315
Lying down in the afternoon was unskillful.

268
00:28:06,414 --> 00:28:09,138
I didn't wake up till seven o'clock and it broke my sleep pattern.

269
00:28:09,420 --> 00:28:10,842
We can say that was unskillful.

270
00:28:11,281 --> 00:28:14,607
But if I then say to myself, well, you're an absolutely useless person.

271
00:28:15,229 --> 00:28:15,869
This is obvious.

272
00:28:16,069 --> 00:28:16,990
What the hell are you doing here?

273
00:28:17,451 --> 00:28:23,801
Then I get into this awful negativity about myself, which is a fiction anyway.

274
00:28:24,845 --> 00:28:33,913
So it's a case of recognizing that the act can be unskillful, but the person need not be criticized.

275
00:28:36,356 --> 00:28:39,440
If those things come up, of course, you can't deny them there.

276
00:28:39,519 --> 00:28:48,028
You can't, just like in feelings of heaviness and these dullness, you can't say, oh, the cell's not there, go away.

277
00:28:48,650 --> 00:28:50,892
No, you have to pay attention to that and let it go.

278
00:28:51,712 --> 00:28:52,894
You have to pay attention to it.

279
00:28:53,228 --> 00:28:55,509
but you don't indulge it by identifying with it.

280
00:28:55,670 --> 00:28:57,372
You recognize it now, that's the self.

281
00:28:58,692 --> 00:29:12,086
And remember that to keep off thought, to come into the body, to stay with the body, because there we're actually experiencing the mind in its rawness as emotion, what we call emotion, feeling, vedana.

282
00:29:14,448 --> 00:29:18,372
So every time the mind wanders, remember, it's indulging itself, whether we like it or not.

283
00:29:19,152 --> 00:29:23,016
Whether we made a decision to do so or not, there's still an impulsion there

284
00:29:23,484 --> 00:29:31,179
So that's why even though we don't mean to get angry, because we let the mind wander, we get more angry and more angry and more angry.

285
00:29:32,401 --> 00:29:33,282
You end up with Prozac.

286
00:29:34,263 --> 00:29:43,961
So it's a case of recognizing that, coming back, coming to the feelings of guilt, feelings of shame, and just staying there with them.

287
00:29:43,981 --> 00:29:45,644
Just allowing them to rise and pass away.

288
00:29:47,313 --> 00:29:51,602
Because you'll never satisfy self-criticism.

289
00:29:52,944 --> 00:29:59,778
I mean, if you hear that voice saying, you really are the most unselfish of people.

290
00:29:59,798 --> 00:30:00,980
I don't know how anybody could love you.

291
00:30:01,843 --> 00:30:05,990
And then you say, well, I'll make up, I'll give something to somebody.

292
00:30:06,372 --> 00:30:08,696
And I'll practice generosity.

293
00:30:08,778 --> 00:30:11,563
And so you do this wonderful gift and give it to somebody, you see.

294
00:30:12,243 --> 00:30:16,531
And then the little voice says, Yes, that was a very wonderful thing.

295
00:30:16,551 --> 00:30:18,115
You did a really wonderful thing.

296
00:30:18,836 --> 00:30:20,239
But you are still horrible.

297
00:30:21,059 --> 00:30:28,913
See, you can't get out of that definition of being horrible by doing something about it because it's there as a conditioning.

298
00:30:29,556 --> 00:30:30,938
So all we can do is,

299
00:30:31,171 --> 00:30:41,040
is allow that statement to come, note it as self-criticism, and go into the feel of it, go into the feel of it, and I'll give it time to dissipate, give it time to dissipate.

300
00:30:44,483 --> 00:31:00,199
So, when it comes to coming back to this renunciation, just one or two things that you might like to try.

301
00:31:02,288 --> 00:31:08,355
The idea of renunciation, of course, is not to create suffering for ourselves, you know, as if we didn't have enough.

302
00:31:09,336 --> 00:31:12,141
The idea of renunciation is to see where the attachment is.

303
00:31:12,701 --> 00:31:20,652
So one stops doing something to feel that attachment towards what you would normally indulge in.

304
00:31:21,553 --> 00:31:28,903
So, you know, just try missing a meal as an experiment, seeing what happens.

305
00:31:32,241 --> 00:31:34,664
And just stay with the feelings of fear.

306
00:31:35,226 --> 00:31:36,928
The body may disappear if I don't eat.

307
00:31:36,968 --> 00:31:37,890
Things like that.

308
00:31:38,871 --> 00:31:41,755
And just stay with it and just feel the fear of it.

309
00:31:41,934 --> 00:31:42,875
That's what you're trying to do.

310
00:31:42,895 --> 00:31:44,377
You're trying to feel the fear.

311
00:31:45,118 --> 00:31:49,525
Remember that underlying all attachment is this anxiety, this fear.

312
00:31:52,710 --> 00:31:57,936
One of the things is to find out what we feel about time.

313
00:31:57,997 --> 00:32:00,240
That can be interesting.

314
00:32:00,742 --> 00:32:06,250
just to find a clock which has a finger going round, and just watch it.

315
00:32:06,830 --> 00:32:11,877
Watch it for an hour, two hours, and just see what happens in your mind.

316
00:32:11,917 --> 00:32:19,950
It can be quite something to listen to yourself, just watching time passing.

317
00:32:19,970 --> 00:32:27,460
Because all this business about trying to achieve something, trying to do something, and I'm wasting my time, that all comes up in great gullops, you see.

318
00:32:28,891 --> 00:32:33,876
So just watching the clock go round, or watching a watch, just tick, tick, tick, going round.

319
00:32:43,068 --> 00:32:56,686
When it comes to this intuitive intelligence, so I'll only say a little bit about that because I'll go into that more deeply later,

320
00:32:58,320 --> 00:33:05,070
This intelligence we have, the Buddha nature within us, this something in us wants to know, where's that come from?

321
00:33:06,252 --> 00:33:20,295
And it's a case of developing that as an intuition, knowing the difference between thought, see, thought is not intuition.

322
00:33:21,877 --> 00:33:24,382
Intuition has to use thought to express itself.

323
00:33:25,083 --> 00:33:28,788
Intuition doesn't know what it knows until it says it to itself.

324
00:33:28,808 --> 00:33:32,233
That's why in your meditation sometimes you might hear these little phrases come up.

325
00:33:32,253 --> 00:33:35,057
Oh, everything's arising and passing away or something like that.

326
00:33:35,439 --> 00:33:37,662
And that's this intuition talking to itself.

327
00:33:39,065 --> 00:33:43,230
And it's one of these peculiarities that it doesn't know what it knows until it tells itself.

328
00:33:43,632 --> 00:33:46,777
And the only way it can tell itself is through words.

329
00:33:47,176 --> 00:33:49,641
Or one way it can tell itself is through words.

330
00:33:50,194 --> 00:33:52,999
Intuition is not feeling.

331
00:33:53,359 --> 00:34:00,290
Don't confuse what people would normally talk about as I have a feeling or intuition with feeling.

332
00:34:00,852 --> 00:34:08,384
Feelings can also be just as delusive as thoughts can be.

333
00:34:09,164 --> 00:34:13,371
But again, this intuitive intelligence expresses itself through feeling.

334
00:34:14,974 --> 00:34:16,556
So just take a very simple thing.

335
00:34:16,822 --> 00:34:26,315
intuitively, in terms of the intellect, expressing through the intellect, we may understand this idea of interconnection, interdependency.

336
00:34:26,936 --> 00:34:30,920
But when it expresses itself through the heart, how does that express itself, you see?

337
00:34:32,182 --> 00:34:33,023
Through love, isn't it?

338
00:34:33,043 --> 00:34:34,445
Compassion.

339
00:34:34,465 --> 00:34:41,295
So compassion, love, sympathetic joy, these are all expressions of interdependency from the heart's point of

340
00:34:43,047 --> 00:34:47,231
And, of course, it's not the body, but it expresses itself through the body.

341
00:34:47,351 --> 00:34:59,400
You've only got to see sports people and see how they react to things and, you know, to see how the intuitive, just that intuitive intelligence expressing itself.

342
00:34:59,420 --> 00:35:03,784
Same with people who perform, you know, actors and musicians.

343
00:35:04,666 --> 00:35:12,092
So the body, heart, mind, the body, all that are avenues in which this intuition travels.

344
00:35:12,307 --> 00:35:13,548
expresses itself.

345
00:35:13,809 --> 00:35:16,512
So somehow, we have to abstract it.

346
00:35:16,552 --> 00:35:24,579
We have to find a way of lifting it out of that embeddedment, that confusion with the psychophysical organism.

347
00:35:25,701 --> 00:35:28,023
And that really is what our meditation is about.

348
00:35:28,143 --> 00:35:31,206
That's why we turn everything into an object.

349
00:35:31,527 --> 00:35:32,648
That's why we look at it.

350
00:35:32,847 --> 00:35:34,208
That's why we look at something.

351
00:35:34,248 --> 00:35:36,030
As soon as you look at it, you can't be it.

352
00:35:39,213 --> 00:35:40,155
If you've got...

353
00:35:40,472 --> 00:35:43,898
If you got into a car and said, well, this is me, they'd take you away.

354
00:35:45,119 --> 00:35:47,081
But here we are in this body and we say, this is me.

355
00:35:48,543 --> 00:35:51,708
So it's the same sort of idea of detachment.

356
00:35:51,889 --> 00:35:53,210
That's what the detachment is.

357
00:35:53,891 --> 00:36:02,362
Lifting this awareness, this intuitive intelligence, this panya, out of its embeddedness to look at what's going on inside us.

358
00:36:05,092 --> 00:36:12,103
And to do that, I always find anyway, personally, that the best motivation is curiosity.

359
00:36:12,722 --> 00:36:26,222
What Zen calls the great doubt, or wanting to know, to excite that interest in our psychology and our bodies, and to see these three characteristics, see how it works.

360
00:36:28,664 --> 00:36:34,492
So this is the sort of thing the Bodhisattva was doing, for eons, for lifetimes.

361
00:36:35,164 --> 00:36:35,985
Trying to get it right.

362
00:36:36,025 --> 00:36:44,280
The other thing is, the other quality is sila, sila, right conduct.

363
00:36:44,639 --> 00:36:54,456
Normally speaking, of course, when we talk about sila or right conduct, it's usually referred to as just what we say and what we do.

364
00:36:55,364 --> 00:37:03,432
But also, you know, for our purposes, we can extend it into the mind because every time we think it's an action, it's an act of karma.

365
00:37:03,653 --> 00:37:07,518
It is a form of sealer, you might say.

366
00:37:08,980 --> 00:37:18,351
And, you know, you can look at just not to harm oneself, you know.

367
00:37:18,905 --> 00:37:19,826
Through our thinking.

368
00:37:20,447 --> 00:37:22,550
Not to harm oneself by overeating.

369
00:37:22,610 --> 00:37:23,693
Not to harm the body.

370
00:37:23,932 --> 00:37:24,634
Oversleeping.

371
00:37:25,755 --> 00:37:29,862
All these wonderful researches into sleep.

372
00:37:30,623 --> 00:37:35,510
And people who sleep five hours are better off than people who sleep nine hours.

373
00:37:36,253 --> 00:37:36,974
It's better for you.

374
00:37:37,514 --> 00:37:42,742
There's a sort of good period between five and seven hours which is good for sleep.

375
00:37:42,882 --> 00:37:45,907
Anything over that is doing harm to the body.

376
00:37:46,815 --> 00:37:54,793
They did these exercises with rats, these poor animals, in which they half-starved one set and overfed the other.

377
00:37:56,016 --> 00:37:59,063
Not surprisingly, the ones who were half-starved lived the longest.

378
00:38:00,507 --> 00:38:02,952
The ones who overfed died of overweight.

379
00:38:05,226 --> 00:38:12,014
One of the things that often troubles us in our meditation is erotic, romantic desires.

380
00:38:12,034 --> 00:38:13,775
It's a very strong pull within us.

381
00:38:14,335 --> 00:38:15,396
So be careful of that.

382
00:38:15,797 --> 00:38:18,099
Because as I say, once the mind trips, you're off.

383
00:38:18,280 --> 00:38:20,503
You've created enormously wonderful good films.

384
00:38:20,822 --> 00:38:26,309
If you'd only written them down, you'd have probably made a fortune by now.

385
00:38:27,009 --> 00:38:32,635
So it's a case of as soon as you see the mind beginning to indulge, be very quick.

386
00:38:33,086 --> 00:38:40,858
And I can set you a little exercise if you haven't heard of it or done it before, but to look to the disgusting nature of the body.

387
00:38:41,458 --> 00:38:45,284
I have to be careful here because you don't want to end up being equally disgusted as you were lusted.

388
00:38:46,905 --> 00:38:59,262
But the idea is that as the figure towards which you feel either erotic or romantic feelings come towards, you either see the body in its more

389
00:38:59,496 --> 00:39:23,697
unpleasant parts and positions and see see the process of aging in that person and this undermines it and the idea is that we train the mind to actually turn the image for us so it'll do it naturally once you've done it a few times it'll just do it naturally for you and as the luster rises and presents his image it'll change in your in your mind just like that it'll do it you see

390
00:39:26,108 --> 00:39:30,833
This is only while, for most of you, you're undertaking the Brahmacharya, you understand.

391
00:39:32,614 --> 00:39:36,159
I wouldn't want to suggest that there isn't a place for the erotic and the romantic in our lives.

392
00:39:37,679 --> 00:39:39,181
I remember it somewhere in my life.

393
00:39:41,264 --> 00:39:41,945
Somewhere in the past.

394
00:39:43,827 --> 00:39:46,509
And that, of course, is a renunciation.

395
00:39:46,528 --> 00:39:48,311
That's part of renunciation, you see.

396
00:39:48,632 --> 00:39:49,972
Renouncing that sense pleasure.

397
00:39:50,527 --> 00:39:52,889
And we have to speak to ourselves properly, you know.

398
00:39:53,471 --> 00:39:57,735
We have to understand why we're doing it, or else you get into a battle with yourself.

399
00:39:58,936 --> 00:40:05,806
And if you do things unwillingly, it creates a wrong attitude within us.

400
00:40:05,826 --> 00:40:10,811
So it's the same with drugs and drink, even at the level of just relying on tea, you know.

401
00:40:11,873 --> 00:40:17,579
That's also, you can look at that as, you know, conduct, you know.

402
00:40:19,331 --> 00:40:23,637
Of course with all this you have to just be careful of not getting too tight a conscience.

403
00:40:26,121 --> 00:40:38,219
One of the great mistakes of the monastic life is presuming that if you keep the rule absolutely perfect then you're bound to move forward.

404
00:40:39,021 --> 00:40:45,351
Or worse, if you're practicing very hard and you don't move forward it means that you're not really keeping the rule properly.

405
00:40:46,532 --> 00:40:47,313
And

406
00:40:47,512 --> 00:40:56,842
I shall end this little tale, I shall end this little discourse with a tale of a particular monk just to show you the error of our ways.

407
00:40:56,862 --> 00:41:09,496
And of course it easily translates into lay life where you get the feeling that everything you're doing is wrong and that just because you're doing something wrong you can't move forward.

408
00:41:09,916 --> 00:41:12,880
You're always slipping into old habits, old negative habits.

409
00:41:14,429 --> 00:41:17,673
So there was a particular monk I knew who was an excellent meditator.

410
00:41:18,695 --> 00:41:21,380
Very fierce, up to a clock in the morning, all that sort of stuff.

411
00:41:22,442 --> 00:41:27,969
And seemingly after some period, not getting anywhere, began to lose confidence.

412
00:41:28,570 --> 00:41:30,894
So he presumed that it must be the Vinaya.

413
00:41:32,297 --> 00:41:39,568
So he began to study the Vinaya and he found, to his horror, that all monks weren't keeping the Vinaya at all.

414
00:41:40,831 --> 00:41:42,293
On two counts specifically.

415
00:41:42,862 --> 00:41:44,664
The upper row was far too big.

416
00:41:45,425 --> 00:41:48,429
According to the original measurements, it was at least half the size.

417
00:41:48,489 --> 00:41:51,755
It was a little cape that you threw over yourself when you went into the village.

418
00:41:52,936 --> 00:41:57,943
And the bowl was definitely not the depth of, I think it's called a cubit.

419
00:41:59,164 --> 00:42:10,980
So, at a particular ceremony, the Katina, which is the time when you have a feast after the rainy season retreat, where people come to make offerings for the

420
00:42:11,702 --> 00:42:17,811
for the sangha, he turned up with a very natty little cape tied around his neck.

421
00:42:19,532 --> 00:42:32,208
And then began doing little arms round, we went on a little arm round, with a proper sized object, which was actually a biscuit tin.

422
00:42:33,016 --> 00:42:36,378
And the general feeling was that he'd gone mad.

423
00:42:37,280 --> 00:42:42,585
Now, as far as he was concerned, he was following the Vinaya strictly.

424
00:42:43,105 --> 00:42:47,389
Unfortunately, he then began to decide that, in fact, Buddha never taught Vipassana.

425
00:42:47,628 --> 00:42:48,911
He only taught Samatha.

426
00:42:49,710 --> 00:42:53,775
And he went to Thailand, and he got shifted from one monastery to the next.

427
00:42:53,815 --> 00:42:56,197
That's what happens.

428
00:42:56,217 --> 00:42:57,038
You just get shifted.

429
00:42:57,077 --> 00:42:58,760
They just tell you to leave.

430
00:42:59,239 --> 00:43:02,483
And he eventually ended up in Australia, where I think he finally disrobed.

431
00:43:03,204 --> 00:43:10,856
And it's a sort of bit of a sadness, really, because he was very keen and very devoted to the practice.

432
00:43:10,876 --> 00:43:22,614
And then just this wrong thought around sila, around conduct, and making that distinction between moral law and rules and regulations.

433
00:43:23,067 --> 00:43:30,840
So remember that even when two people, well, even by yourself, but especially when two people live in the same place, you have a veneer.

434
00:43:31,641 --> 00:43:43,320
You have your own little rules and regulations, like you leave your shoes in a certain place and you don't leave them anywhere else and you have to close the door and you don't pull the chain of the toilet at certain times during the night and things like that.

435
00:43:43,637 --> 00:43:49,771
So all these little rules and regulations begin to build up whenever two people live together.

436
00:43:49,791 --> 00:43:56,625
And of course, even when you live on your own, you end up having little rules and regulations which you're not aware of until somebody comes and lives with you.

437
00:43:57,166 --> 00:43:59,871
And then you realize that you don't want them to wash the pots like that.

438
00:44:00,072 --> 00:44:01,173
You do it like this.

439
00:44:03,195 --> 00:44:08,545
And it causes enormous anger and all sorts of silly stuff.

440
00:44:09,628 --> 00:44:13,454
So, again, this business of right conduct.

441
00:44:13,815 --> 00:44:17,824
We can look at our actions from the point of view of not doing harm to ourselves.

442
00:44:17,903 --> 00:44:18,684
That's the main point.

443
00:44:20,528 --> 00:44:22,411
There are two other things that I want to say.

444
00:44:22,572 --> 00:44:23,954
The upeka principle.

445
00:44:24,474 --> 00:44:28,163
It is a total receptivity.

446
00:44:28,583 --> 00:44:32,373
Upeka, you'll hear it used in various ways.

447
00:44:32,753 --> 00:44:34,518
One of them is neutral feelings.

448
00:44:34,998 --> 00:44:42,315
But here, we're really talking about an attitude of complete openness, complete receptivity.

449
00:44:42,295 --> 00:44:44,878
It's a bit like a judge in a way.

450
00:44:45,297 --> 00:44:51,864
We expect a judge not to get caught up in the arguments of these clever lawyers and not to get caught up in the emotion of the crowd.

451
00:44:52,385 --> 00:44:58,152
So, as it were, it's an attitude of being completely open to whatever your heart and mind have to offer you.

452
00:44:58,632 --> 00:45:02,715
You know, a real openness.

453
00:45:03,657 --> 00:45:05,079
You know, hold nothing back, you see.

454
00:45:06,159 --> 00:45:09,744
Of course, when you find yourself getting tight, then investigate that.

455
00:45:09,824 --> 00:45:10,264
What is it?

456
00:45:10,384 --> 00:45:10,704
Fear?

457
00:45:10,925 --> 00:45:11,465
Aversion?

458
00:45:11,766 --> 00:45:12,065
You see?

459
00:45:14,442 --> 00:45:17,085
And finally, mudita, joy.

460
00:45:17,505 --> 00:45:21,829
I really do feel that at the end of the day, we ought to rejoice.

461
00:45:22,911 --> 00:45:32,663
I mean, for heaven's sake, we've been sat here for I don't know how many hours, walking around and restraining ourselves, and at the end of the day, all we can think about is what a horrible day we had.

462
00:45:33,324 --> 00:45:40,351
So it's good at the end of the day to reflect on the fact that we've been training, and we've been moving forward.

463
00:45:41,012 --> 00:45:44,195
And even though it might feel sometimes a spiritual life as one

464
00:45:44,530 --> 00:45:54,141
well-known Hindu saint in Sri Lanka used to say, the spiritual life sometimes feels it's one step forward, two steps back.

465
00:45:55,021 --> 00:46:09,458
The fact is that every evening I really feel that it's a good practice to rejoice about one's spiritual life and to feel happiness around it, that we are actually doing what is good for us and good for others.

466
00:46:10,467 --> 00:46:23,498
So that quality of mudita, that quality of rejoicing in oneself, because it's often translated as just sympathetic joy, you know, that you can only be joyful when somebody else is joyful, you see.

467
00:46:23,697 --> 00:46:25,079
But we can be joyful in ourselves.

468
00:46:26,402 --> 00:46:35,518
And I have found that the more I practice these virtues towards myself, the more it's easier for me to practice towards the others.

469
00:46:36,179 --> 00:46:46,177
So that goes back to our metta practice, which always begins classically with offering ourselves metta before we offer it to others.

470
00:46:46,900 --> 00:46:54,371
We tend to find that difficult because of our negativities towards ourselves, so we have to come round it another way.

471
00:46:55,152 --> 00:47:08,311
But even so, we can see that if we can think of these virtues as something we can develop towards ourselves, then I think they become more immediately important to us.

472
00:47:08,913 --> 00:47:08,992
Hmm?

473
00:47:10,693 --> 00:47:18,864
So that's what the Buddha was doing for all these countless ages and lifetime after lifetime.

474
00:47:19,385 --> 00:47:22,677
The Bodhisattva in his vow to become fully self-enlightened.
